  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Cash Information Management Service Development</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">NLRC-510 &amp; 121 team
British Red Cross Cash Hub
IFRC Cash IM team
National Societies</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">NLRC-510 will develop a Cash IM service and products, which will help national societies to implement cash programs supported by information management systems, digital technology and use data analytics to get good insights and reports. We will create a scale up and future plan for 121. The most feasible route to take with the system is to productize validated key components of it.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Tbd</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The objective of this project is to change the 510 development team to a rapid prototyping team with a clear global service offering to the IFRC Network, and to initiate a first set of support projects to national societies. When the service is initiated and national societies are requesting the services, the cost-recovery model of 510 will ensure the sustainability of the initial investment from the IH extra projects fund.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Within the IFRC Network more cash programs are planned and conducted than ever before. The current COVID appeal has already highlighted 22 national societies in the Africa region that will do cash programs for livelihoods. Many of those national societies have limited to no experience with cash programming. They find programmatic cash expertise through online courses and IFRC delegates. There however remains a gap in the IFRC Network on Cash Information Management experts. This gap is critical because the information management component in cash programming is significant. Additionally there is a big gap in training opportunities and standard toolkits for national societies to implement cash information management.</narrative>
  </description>
